<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-520-818  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 520 818.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Weekly  August 3 1989 n1175 p14(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Copyrights and wrongs. (1988 Copyright, Designs and Patents Acttakes effect)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Hoyle, Chris.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Great Britain's 1988 Copyright, Designs and Patents Act helps thecomputer industry by providing new rights and protections and byclarifying previously murky aspects of the law.andP;  Legislation makesit makes it clear that in the case of computer-generated software,the author is the person who made the arrangements necessary forthe creation of the work.andP;  The act clearly makes liable personswho sell or supply devices that circumvent copyright mechanisms insoftware or who publish information on creating or obtaining suchdevices.andP;  The act makes it easier to prove ownership of a softwarecopyright, especially in the case where a large team created aprogram.andP;  The act makes clear that the use of a program on acomputer usually constitutes copying.andP;  The act's authorsdeliberately left open the 'look and feel' question.andP;  Ultimately acourt must determine look and feel by weighing all the evidence ina particular case.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Statute:   Great Britain. Copyright, Designs and Patents Act 1988(interpretation and construction).andO;Topic:     CopyrightPatentComputer IndustrySoftware PublishersLegislationUnited Kingdom.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>